## Phase Status

Phase 1 is done. Phase 2 is done. Phase 3 is done. Phase 4 is done. Phase 5
is done. Phase 6 is done.

The Phase 1 scaffold adds the unified public workspace vocabulary beside the
existing isolated-workspace exports.

The Phase 2 slice makes `sandbox.isolation.enter` and the test compact-remount
path accept caller-facing `workspace_root`, resolves that root to the
LayerStack workspace binding internally, and keeps legacy `layer_stack_root`
accepted through explicit compatibility adapters. It does not implement the
future create/run/capture/destroy lifecycle APIs.

Phase 2 adversarial review follow-up tightened the root-resolution contract:
discovered bindings must live at their declared `layer_stack_root`, cached
runtime state now tracks `workspace_root` as part of its binding identity,
stateful resolution no longer bypasses ambiguity checks, malformed dual-root
payloads cannot silently fall back to legacy `layer_stack_root`, and
test-remount invalid root requests preserve `invalid_argument` error shaping.

The Phase 3 slice moves Host command workspace lifecycle ownership out of
hidden command start behavior and into `WorkspaceRuntime`. Host command routes
now ask the runtime to resolve the legacy `layer_stack_root` compatibility
binding, acquire the bounded base lease, create the `EphemeralWorkspace`, and
then hand a command context to `CommandOps`. `CommandOps` still owns process
spawning, wait/progress/stdin/cancel mechanics, registry state, transcripts,
capture, and finalization.

The Phase 4 slice makes `WorkspaceRuntime` the command/file route authority.
Runtime route contexts now decide active isolated handle vs Host/direct
fallback and return stable route trace facts to adapters. Command adapters parse
wire args, record returned route metadata, and invoke `CommandOps` with the
returned execution target while the runtime-owned mode gate remains held during
command start. File adapters parse wire args, record returned route metadata,
invoke the selected direct or isolated backend, and ask the runtime to complete
isolated liveness touches after successful isolated file operations.

The Phase 5 slice adds explicit non-publishing capture in `WorkspaceRuntime`.
Host capture reads the runtime-owned `HostWorkspaceLifecycle` upperdir. Isolated
capture resolves a unified public handle to the active isolated binding and
reads that handle's upperdir. Both paths hold the existing workspace mode gate,
reject nonzero active command counts before walking the upperdir, return changed
paths, changed path kinds, protected drops, and optional stats, and never call
LayerStack publish/OCC APIs. Metadata-only capture now honors
`materialize_payloads: false` without reading regular-file payload bodies. Host
capture remains lifecycle-scoped until public Host create/handle custody exists.
No public wire adapter was added in this slice because the current catalog has
no `capture_changes` op and `ops.json` regeneration is explicitly forbidden.

The Phase 6 slice moves workspace crate code into the responsibility-based
folder structure without changing behavior. Shared overlay primitives now live
under `overlay/`; isolated workspace create/destroy/recovery/lease helpers live
under `lifecycle/`; remount state, report/plan, and apply logic live under
`lifecycle/remount/`; holder control, setns-runner prep, FD mapping, cgroup
creation, and namespace plan types live under `namespace/`; Host and isolated
mode exports route through thin `network_mode/` adapters; and veth/IP-pool,
rtnetlink, and netfilter dedicated-network setup/cleanup internals live under
`isolated_network_setup/`. Legacy root `capture`, `dirs`, and `tree` modules,
plus isolated-workspace namespace/network modules, remain only as thin
re-export shims. No Phase 7 holder/setns-only execution changes, Host
holder-backed namespace creation, Phase 8 legacy export retirement, publish
behavior change, capture behavior change, packaging, live E2E, or `ops.json`
regeneration was implemented.

